The fluorescence spectra of EY and the reaction mixture of EY and Ag(I) are shown in Fig. 3
                        . The maximum excitation (λex
                        ) and emission wavelengths (λem
                        ) of EY are at 515 nm and 540 nm respectively. When EY reacted with Ag(I) and formed an ionic association, the fluorescence of EY was quenched significantly. The fluorescence decreased with the increase of Ag(I) concentration and showed a linear relationship in the range of 9.3 × 10−3– 0.46 µM. The detection limit is 2.2 nM. Compared with the spectrometric method described above, the sensitivity of the fluorescence method is considerably improved.

As it can be seen in Fig. 7
                           , when Ag(I) reacted with EY to form a complex, the absorption spectrum changed. When Ag(I) was in excess to ensure complete reaction of EY, an absorption spectrum different from that of both EY and Ag(I) was produced. The maximum absorption wavelength (λmax
                           ) of EY redshifted from 514 nm to 521 nm, Δλ was 7 nm, and the molar absorption coefficient (ε) decreased from 4.6 × 104 L mol−1 cm−1 before the reaction (514 nm) to 1.2 × 104 L mol−1 cm−1 after the reaction (521 nm).
